          "title": "The theological climax — 'Be holy, for I am holy'",
          "body": "The entire chapter pivots on two verses (11:44-45) that provide its only explicit rationale. 'For I am the LORD your God. Consecrate yourselves therefore, and be holy, for I am holy.' Two grounds are given: divine identity ('I am the LORD your God') and redemptive history ('I am the LORD who brought you up from the land of Egypt to be your God'). The holiness command is not grounded in hygiene theory, cultural differentiation from Canaanites, or ecological wisdom — though these may be secondary effects. It is grounded in who God is and what He has done. Peter quotes this verse verbatim in 1 Peter 1:15-16 and applies it to Christian conduct — demonstrating that the imitatio Dei principle of 'be holy as I am holy' transcends the specific dietary legislation while the underlying theological logic remains binding. Swindoll (Living Close to the Flame) observes that the danger of Leviticus is reading it as bureaucratic regulation when it is in fact the most personal of commands: the God who rescued you is defining what it means to become like Him."
