          "title": "The purpose statement — badal, the separation that shapes a people",
          "body": "The chapter closes with a formal summary (11:46-47) and a purpose statement built on the verb badal: 'to make a distinction between the unclean and the clean, and between the edible creature and the creature which is not to be eaten.' Badal is the verb God used at creation to separate light from darkness, water from water, day from night (Genesis 1:4, 6, 7, 14, 18). By using it here, the Torah presents Israel's dietary discipline as a participation in God's own creative act of ordering. The Israelite who navigates the market and the table by these distinctions is not merely following rules — he is enacting in daily life the same habit of distinction that constitutes a holy God's engagement with the world. John Calvin (Harmony of the Four Last Books of Moses) rightly notes that while the ceremonial laws are abrogated in Christ, the moral logic beneath them — that the people of God are to be visibly, tangibly distinct in every domain of life — remains permanently binding in whatever form the new covenant takes."
